         <abstract>
            <p>Numerical methods for bifurcation problems of the form \begin{equation*}\tag* Ly = \lambda f(y), &amp; By = 0\end{equation*} where $f(0) = 0$ and $f'(0) \neq 0$, are considered. Here $y$ is a scalar function, $\lambda$ is a real scalar, $L$ is a linear differential operator and $By = 0$ represents some linear homogeneous two-point boundary conditions. Under certain assumptions, it is shown that if $(\ast)$ is replaced by an appropriate difference scheme, then there exists a unique branch of nontrivial solutions of the discrete problem in a neighborhood of a branch of nontrivial solutions of $(\ast)$ bifurcating from the trivial solution and that the discrete branch converges to the continuous one. Error estimates are derived and an illustrative numerical example is included.</p>
          </abstract>
